<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This East African species is commonly grown as an ornamental vine and easily escapes from cultivation. It is widely naturalised in warm-temperate and subtropical areas across the world to such an extent that it is often considered to be an environmental weed. It was recently reported for the first time in the Canary Islands from several localities in La Palma, where it is naturalised now (
<bibRefCitation author="Otto, R" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509398" refString="Otto, R, Verloove, F, 2018. New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species - Part 2. Collectanea Botanica 37" title="New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species - Part 2" volume="37" year="2018">Otto and Verloove 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In January 2017, it was observed for the first time in Tenerife, in a ravine in an urban environment in Tejina (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F6510171" captionText="Figure 10. Thunbergia alata, San Cristobal de La Laguna (Tejina), January 2017." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e62878.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/494351" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">10</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
